# Module Structure Design Standard

## Purpose

This document defines the required module structure standard for the Hendren Platform.

This is not a suggestion.
This is not a style preference.
This is the repo standard.

The platform is moving to a repo-as-source-of-truth model. That means the repo must become structurally trustworthy, predictable, and maintainable. A growing platform cannot be allowed to grow structurally messy at the same time.

Clean things stay clean.
Messy things get messier.
We are choosing the first path on purpose.

## Core Decision

The Hendren Platform will use a **module-first, route-local, composition-based inheritance model**.

That means:

- every substantial feature follows the same module shape,
- route files stay thin,
- shared behavior flows downward from common layers,
- shared UI is inherited through primitives and section shells,
- domain logic is centralized,
- module-specific code stays local to the module,
- no module is allowed to become a one-file god object.

## What Inheritance Means Here

Inheritance in this repo does **not** mean React class inheritance.

Inheritance here means **layered reuse through composition**.

The reuse hierarchy is:

1. **Design tokens**
   - colors
   - spacing
   - radii
   - shadows
   - type scale
   - semantic state colors

2. **UI primitives**
   - Button
   - Input
   - Select
   - Textarea
   - Checkbox
   - Card
   - Badge
   - Tabs
   - Modal
   - Spinner

3. **Shared app patterns**
   - PageShell
   - PageHeader
   - ModuleToolbar
   - SectionHeader
   - FormSection
   - SaveCancelBar
   - EmptyState
   - ErrorState
   - LoadingState
   - DataTable
   - MetricCard

4. **Domain patterns**
   - permission matrix editor pattern
   - schedule editor pattern
   - procurement linking pattern
   - issue/task list pattern
   - contact management pattern
   - worksheet-family pattern

5. **Module assembly**
   - Jobs
   - Schedule
   - Companies
   - Internal Users
   - Pricing Sources / Bids
   - future modules

That is the inheritance model.
Changes to shared behavior must happen as high in that ladder as practical.

## Non-Negotiable Rules

### 1. Thin route files

`page.tsx` is a route entry point, not a dumping ground.

A route file may:

- read params,
- gate access,
- load data,
- choose which components to assemble,
- pass props down.

A route file may not become the permanent home for:

- many helper utilities,
- repeated style definitions,
- several unrelated forms,
- deep mutation logic,
- multiple large sections,
- domain rules,
- editor orchestration.

### 2. Module-local before global

If code is only used by one module, it belongs inside that module.

Do not move code into global folders just because it feels reusable.
It is only global when it is truly cross-module.

### 3. One source of truth per concern

Every concern gets one owner.

Examples:

- one owner for design tokens,
- one owner for a button primitive,
- one owner for permission rules,
- one owner for schedule dependency logic,
- one owner for a form schema,
- one owner for route state.

No duplicated logic across sibling files.
No duplicated style decisions across modules.
No duplicated state ownership.

### 4. Shared UI is inherited, not copied

If three modules use the same pattern, that is one primitive or one shared shell.
It is not three copied versions.

### 5. Domain logic does not live in UI files

Presentation helpers can live in route-local `_lib`.
Business rules cannot.

Anything authoritative belongs in shared domain code.

### 6. No god components

Any file that owns all of the following is already wrong:

- page shell,
- tab system,
- local state,
- CRUD handlers,
- helper utilities,
- formatting,
- section rendering,
- and repeated style objects.

That file must be split.

## Standard Module Template

Every substantial module should follow this shape.

```text
src/
  app/
    (app)/
      <module>/
        page.tsx
        loading.tsx                # if useful
        error.tsx                  # if useful
        actions.ts                 # route-local server actions only
        types.ts                   # route-local derived types only
        _components/
          <Module>Page.tsx
          <Module>Header.tsx
          <Module>Toolbar.tsx
          <Module>List.tsx
          <Module>Form.tsx
          sections/
            <Module>InfoSection.tsx
            <Module>ActivitySection.tsx
            <Module>FilesSection.tsx
        _hooks/
          use<Module>Filters.ts
          use<Module>Draft.ts
          use<Module>Editor.ts
        _lib/
          constants.ts
          formatters.ts
          mappers.ts
          selectors.ts
          validators.ts
        [id]/
          page.tsx
          loading.tsx
          error.tsx
          actions.ts
          _components/
            <Module>DetailPage.tsx
            <Module>Tabs.tsx
            sections/
              InfoSection.tsx
              ActivitySection.tsx
              RelatedRecordsSection.tsx
          _hooks/
            use<Module>DetailState.ts
          _lib/
            formatters.ts
            validators.ts
```

